A malformed or non-ASCII error body from the backend should produce a *truncated error message* and a normal `Err(...)` that propagates up the call stack — exactly like the sibling helper `truncate_utf8` (`openai_compat.rs:682`) already does, by walking back to a char boundary with `is_char_boundary`. One bad response should affect at most one request; the daemon must stay up.

### Actual behavior

`&trimmed[..MAX_LEN]` panics when `MAX_LEN` (240) is not a char boundary. The workspace `[profile.release]` in the root `Cargo.toml` sets `panic = "abort"`, so the panic aborts the whole `genie-core` process rather than unwinding one task. This kills `/api/health` and, because the voice loop awaits the LLM call on the main task, the voice service dies with it. A single malformed/non-ASCII backend response is enough to take the daemon down (very plausible when `genie-ai-runtime` is under memory pressure and emits a partial/localized body).

