In `crates/engine/src/game/triggers.rs`, when multiple abilities trigger simultaneously the engine orders them with a **binary** "is this the active player?" key. Every *non-active* player is collapsed into a single bucket ordered only by timestamp, so in games with two or more non-active players (Commander / multiplayer) the triggers are not put on the stack in turn order as the Comprehensive Rules require.

```rust
// crates/engine/src/game/triggers.rs:1825
// CR 603.3b: Active player's triggers are ordered before non-active player's triggers.
// Within same controller, order by timestamp.
pending.sort_by_key(|t| {
    let is_nap = if t.pending.controller == state.active_player {
        0
    } else {
        1
    };
    (is_nap, t.pending.timestamp)   // <- all non-active players share rank 1
});

// Reverse so NAP triggers are placed first (bottom of stack), AP triggers last (top).
pending.reverse();
```

The `is_nap` key is `0` for the active player and `1` for **every** non-active player, with `timestamp` as the only tiebreaker. That cannot reproduce turn order among multiple non-active players.

## What the CR requires

Verified verbatim against `docs/MagicCompRules.txt`:

```
603.3b If multiple abilities have triggered since the last time a player received priority,
       each player, in APNAP order, puts triggered abilities they control on the stack
       in an order of their choosing. (See rule 101.4.) ...
101.4  If multiple players would make choices ... the active player ... makes any choices
       required, then the next player in turn order ... followed by the remaining nonactive
       players in turn order. ...
```

So abilities are placed on the stack in **APNAP order**: the active player first, then **each remaining player in turn order** — not "active player, then all non-active players lumped together by timestamp."

The codebase already has the correct helper, `players::apnap_order` (`crates/engine/src/game/players.rs:78`):

```rust
