### What happens

`chrono_lite_now()` in `crates/feed-scraper/src/main.rs` builds the date from a `days % 365` value:

```rust
let remaining_days = days % 365;
let months = remaining_days / 30 + 1;
let day = remaining_days % 30 + 1;
```

`remaining_days / 30 + 1` reaches **13** for the last days of the cycle, and `% 365` drifts the date by a day each year. The `updated` field written into the MTGGoldfish feed JSON (refreshed by `refresh-feeds`) can therefore be a malformed timestamp such as `2025-13-06`.

### Expected

A valid ISO 8601 UTC date (month in `01`–`12`, day correct for the month, leap years handled).

## Summary

When two or more players meet a loss condition in the same state-based-action check, the engine eliminates them **sequentially** and runs the game-over check **after each elimination**. The first elimination sees the other dying player still "alive" and latches `GameOver { winner: Some(other) }`; the second elimination's game-over check early-returns because the result is already set. The engine therefore declares a player who has *also* lost as the **winner**, when CR 104.4a mandates a **draw**.

State-based actions are required to be performed **simultaneously as a single event** (CR 704.3). The engine violates this by interleaving the game-over check between individual eliminations.

The loss check collects all losers, then eliminates them one at a time (`crates/engine/src/game/sba.rs`):

```rust
fn check_player_life(state: &mut GameState, events: &mut Vec<GameEvent>, any_performed: &mut bool) {
    let to_eliminate: Vec<PlayerId> = state.players.iter()
        .filter(|p| !p.is_eliminated && !p.is_phased_out() && p.life <= 0)
        .filter(|p| !player_has_cant_lose(state, p.id))
        .map(|p| p.id)
        .collect();

    for loser in to_eliminate {
        events.push(GameEvent::PlayerLost { player_id: loser });
        super::elimination::eliminate_player(state, loser, events);  // <- runs check_game_over each iteration
        *any_performed = true;
    }
}
```

`eliminate_player` runs `check_game_over` after every single elimination (`crates/engine/src/game/elimination.rs`), and `check_game_over` latches the result and early-returns once set:

```rust
fn check_game_over(state: &mut GameState, events: &mut Vec<GameEvent>) {
    if state.match_phase != MatchPhase::InGame
        || matches!(state.waiting_for, WaitingFor::GameOver { .. })   // <- early-return once latched
    { return; }
    let living: Vec<PlayerId> = state.players.iter().filter(|p| !p.is_eliminated).map(|p| p.id).collect();
    ...
    if living.len() <= 1 {
        let winner = living.first().copied();   // <- the *other* still-dying player
        state.waiting_for = WaitingFor::GameOver { winner };
    }
}
```

The same sequential-eliminate-then-check pattern is used by every SBA loss check — `check_player_life`, `check_draw_from_empty`, `check_poison_counters`, and `check_commander_damage` — so the bug applies to all loss conditions, and to simultaneity *across* conditions within a single SBA check (one player at 0 life while another has 10 poison).

## What the CR requires

Verified against `docs/MagicCompRules.txt`:

- CR 704.3: "…the game checks for [SBA conditions]… All applicable state-based actions are performed **simultaneously as a single event**…"
- CR 704.5a: "If a player has 0 or less life, that player loses the game."
- CR 104.4a: "If all the players remaining in a game lose simultaneously, the game is a **draw**."

So when every remaining player meets a loss condition in one SBA event, the result is a draw (`winner: None`), not a win for …

