## Summary

In `crates/engine/src/parser/oracle_effect/imperative.rs`, the `"gain" | "gains"` arm of `parse_imperative_family_ast` disambiguates the clause with a substring check:

```rust
"gain" | "gains" => {
    if nom_primitives::scan_contains(lower, "control of") {
        // gain control of ...
    } else if nom_primitives::scan_contains(lower, "life") {
        // numeric life-gain
    } else {
        // keyword grant
    }
}
```

`scan_contains(lower, "life")` matches the **substring** "life" — which is also contained in the keyword **"lifelink"**. So `"gain lifelink"` is routed to the numeric life-gain parser, which finds no amount, returns `None`, and the clause falls through to `Effect::Unimplemented`. The keyword-grant branch is never reached.

## Failure mode

`Blessing of Belzenlok` — "Target creature gets +2/+1 until end of turn. **If it's legendary, it also gains lifelink until end of turn.**" The conditional + duration parse correctly, but the inner effect resolves to `Unimplemented { name: "gain", description: "gain lifelink" }` instead of a Lifelink grant.

Affected cards (an `Unimplemented` gain-lifelink clause): Blessing of Belzenlok, Bre of Clan Stoutarm, Archon's Glory, Revelation of Power, Wedding Invitation, Greymond, Aragorn (Company Leader), Case of the Gorgon's Kiss, and more — ~15 cards carry a `gains lifelink` / `gains flying and lifelink` clause that currently misroutes.

## Expected behavior

`"gain lifelink"` (and `"gain flying and lifelink"`, etc.) grants the keyword(s), exactly as `"gain flying"` does. Genuine life-gain clauses (`"gain 3 life"`) continue to route to the numeric parser.

## Suggested fix

Try the keyword-grant parser (`try_parse_gain_keyword`) **before** the bare `"life"` substring check. It already returns `None` unless it finds a real keyword, so genuine life-gain clauses still fall through to the numeric branch.

## Component

- `crates/engine/src/parser/oracle_effect/imperative.rs` — `parse_imperative_family_ast`, the `"gain" | "gains"` dispatch.

